GoFTPd Changelog
================

1.0.6b
------

- Unreleased changes go here.

1.0.5b
------

- Reworked the in-memory VFS so directory listings use direct child indexes
  instead of broad global scans.
- Added cached race-state reads and RaceDB-backed release search to reduce
  hot-path overhead during browsing and racing.
- Switched the shipped ACL examples to root-based paths (`/PRE`, `/MP3`, etc.)
  and cleaned up the structured permissions examples.
- Moved PRE affil visibility management fully into the PRE plugin so
  `affils.yml` stays the source of truth and generated ACL rules stay in sync.
- Added slave-control hardening:
  - IP allowlist support
  - auth-failure temp bans
  - persistent denylist file
  - `SITE SLAVEBANS`, `SITE SLAVEBAN`, and `SITE SLAVEUNBAN`
- Added the built-in `slowupkick` plugin to warn and kick slow uploaders and
  downloaders, with staff-channel announcements.
- Added DH1080 auto-exchange for encrypted PM/NOTICE traffic in the sitebot.
- Fixed a race where very fast slave acknowledgements could arrive before the
  master had registered its waiter, causing random upload timeout failures.
- Fixed zip zipscript handling for `0DAY` and `EBOOKS`:
  - blocks manual `file_id.diz` uploads
  - extracts `file_id.diz` from uploaded archives
  - parses more real-world DIZ count formats
  - uses the recovered count for progress, halfway, and complete banners
- Fixed missing or inconsistent `NEW` announces by synthesizing `NEW` from the
  first real upload when a clean `MKDIR` announce was missed.
- Fixed dated-dir announce handling for layouts such as
  `/0DAY/2026-04-26/release/`.
- Fixed section resolution for nested roots like `FOREIGN`, `PRE`, and
  `ARCHIVE` so announces route to the correct child section.
- Fixed `SITE RESCAN` for audio releases so cached music metadata such as genre
  and year is refreshed again for complete banners.
- Fixed parent incomplete markers for zip releases.
- Fixed root and section banner leakage so race banners only appear where they
  make sense, and made the normal CWD banner configurable.
- Fixed topic command behavior and PM encryption flow in the sitebot.

1.0.4b
------

- Added the built-in zipscript module with tighter ZIP and SFV handling.
- Added `SITE BW` plus sitebot `!bw`.
- Added `SITE REMERGE`.
- Added request plugin improvements and public request handling.
- Added configurable log mirroring and log retention controls.
- Added music genre to COMPLETE banners.
- Added section directory creation on slaves and better request visibility on
  CWD.
- Fixed nested section routing and release detection for sitebot announces.
- Fixed incomplete markers for dated release dirs and section roots.
- Fixed private-path event suppression and improved normal-user listing
  behavior.

1.0.3b
------

- Introduced the unified `setup.sh` flow and split plugin configs into
  `config.yml.dist` templates.
- Added setup-driven TLS certificate generation and more complete interactive
  config handling.
- Added self-service IP management and autonuke support.
- Added version propagation into startup banners and media banners.
- Added built-in site user and group management improvements.
- Improved logging defaults, disabled debug in shipped examples, and tightened
  rehash output.
- Improved race stat formatting and restored cached SFV state during reconcile.

1.0.2b
------

- Large architecture refresh of daemon and sitebot internals.
- Added async plugin flow, unified config layout, and broader IRC output
  cleanup.
- Added `SITE PRE`, PREBW support, dated sections, `SITE REHASH`, and
  `SITE INVITE`.
- Added MLST/MLSD support and cbftp-related listing fixes.
- Added metadata lookup groundwork and IMDb rewrite work.
- Improved race speed handling and general announce routing.

1.0.1b
------

- Fixed bcrypt password handling.
- Fixed wrong output from several SITE commands.
- Improved race rendering and race database plumbing.
- Expanded site user management behavior.

1.0.0b
------

- Initial beta baseline for the current GoFTPd codebase.
- Core FTP daemon, sitebot, VFS, ACL, and race-tracking foundations in place.
